

CI/CD Pipeline Failures – Real-Time Scenarios & Troubleshooting
Q) What kind of errors have you seen in your CI/CD pipeline and how did you resolve them?
Answer:
In real-time DevOps projects, I have handled multiple types of failures across CI/CD pipelines, Docker, Kubernetes, Terraform, cloud infrastructure, and security tools.

Whenever a pipeline fails, my approach is:

Identify the exact stage where failure occurred
Analyze logs carefully
Find the root cause
Fix the issue with minimal downtime
Implement preventive automation to avoid recurrence
Below are some real-time scenarios I handled in production environments.


1) Build Failure Due to Dependency Issues
Real-Time Scenario
In one project, the Jenkins pipeline started failing during the Maven build stage after developers merged new code into the main branch.

Error
Could not resolve dependencies

Version conflict detected

Package not found


Root Cause
One library version was upgraded
Another internal package still depended on the old version
Corrupted Maven cache
Troubleshooting
Checked Jenkins console logs
Verified recent pom.xml changes
Checked Nexus repository artifacts
Cleared Maven cache:
rm -rf ~/.m2/repository


Resolution
Fixed dependency version mismatch
Updated parent pom.xml
Rebuilt the pipeline successfully
Prevention
Implemented dependency version standards
Added dependency validation in CI pipeline

2) Docker Image Build Failure
Real-Time Scenario
Docker image build failed during Azure DevOps pipeline execution.

Error
No space left on device

Docker build failed

Package install failure


Root Cause
Jenkins agent disk became full
Old Docker images consumed storage
Proxy/network issue while downloading packages
Troubleshooting
Logged into Jenkins agent server
Checked disk usage:
df -h

docker system df


Removed unused Docker images:
docker system prune -a


Validated Dockerfile changes
Verified internet/proxy connectivity
Resolution
Cleaned unused Docker images
Optimized Docker layers
Added automated cleanup jobs
Additional Real-Time Issues
Wrong base image tag
DockerHub rate limits
Missing package repositories
Best Practice
Used Docker layer caching to reduce build time significantly.


3) SonarQube Quality Gate Failure
Real-Time Scenario
Pipeline failed before deployment because SonarQube quality gate failed.

Error
Quality Gate Failed

Critical vulnerabilities detected

Coverage below threshold


What Actually Happens
Pipeline waits for SonarQube analysis results.
If:

Code coverage is low
Critical vulnerabilities exist
Code smells exceed threshold
then deployment gets blocked automatically.

Troubleshooting
Opened SonarQube dashboard
Reviewed:
Vulnerabilities
Code smells
Duplications
Coverage reports
Worked with developers to fix issues
Resolution
Added unit tests
Removed hardcoded secrets
Reduced duplicate code
Best Practice
Block pipeline only for Critical/Blocker issues
Allow minor warnings

4) Terraform Pipeline Failure
Real-Time Scenario
Terraform deployment failed while provisioning AWS infrastructure.

Error
Error acquiring state lock

Resource already exists


Root Cause
Another Terraform execution already running
Infrastructure drift
State file inconsistency
Troubleshooting
Checked Terraform backend
Verified DynamoDB state lock
Executed:
terraform refresh

terraform plan


Resolution
Removed stale state lock
Imported manually created resources
Reconfigured remote backend
Best Practice
Used:

S3 backend
DynamoDB locking
Separate workspaces for environments

5) Expired Credentials / Tokens
Real-Time Scenario
Pipeline failed while pushing Docker images to AWS ECR.

Error
Token expired

Authentication failed

AccessDeniedException


Root Cause
AWS temporary credentials expired
Azure service principal secret expired
Kubernetes token rotation issue
Troubleshooting
Verified IAM credentials
Checked Jenkins credentials store
Validated cloud permissions
Resolution
Rotated credentials
Reconfigured secrets
Integrated HashiCorp Vault
Best Practice
Avoid hardcoded credentials. Use:

Vault
IAM Roles
Kubernetes Secrets
Managed Identity

6) Kubernetes Deployment Failure
Real-Time Scenario
Deployment failed after successful image build.

Common Errors
CrashLoopBackOff
ImagePullBackOff
OOMKilled
Readiness probe failed

Scenario 1 — ImagePullBackOff
Root Cause
Wrong image tag
Image not pushed properly
Registry authentication issue
Troubleshooting
kubectl describe pod pod-name


Resolution
Fixed image tag
Reconfigured imagePullSecrets

Scenario 2 — CrashLoopBackOff
Root Cause
Application startup failure
Missing environment variables
Database connectivity issue
Troubleshooting
kubectl logs pod-name


Resolution
Fixed environment variables
Updated ConfigMaps
Added retry handling

Scenario 3 — OOMKilled
Root Cause
Container exceeded memory limits.

Resolution
Configured proper memory limits:

resources:

  requests:

    memory: "512Mi"

  limits:

    memory: "1Gi"


Best Practice
Always configure:

Liveness probes
Readiness probes
Resource limits

7) Jenkins / Azure DevOps Agent Connectivity Issues
Real-Time Scenario
Pipelines were stuck in queue for a long time.

Error
Agent disconnected

No available agents


Root Cause
Agent VM down
Java process crashed
Disk full
Network issue
Troubleshooting
Logged into agent server
Checked service status:
systemctl status jenkins-agent


Verified CPU, memory, and connectivity
Resolution
Restarted agent service
Increased auto-scaling agents
Added monitoring alerts
Best Practice
Use:

Kubernetes dynamic agents
Auto-scaling runners
Spot instances

8) Security Scan Blocking Pipeline
Real-Time Scenario
